      <hedline>
        <hl1>Imus in the Mainstream</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Don Imus letter responds to Jan 11 editorial's criticism of his radio show as forum for New Jersey Sen Robert Torricelli; says The New York Times Company has spent hundreds of thousands of dollars over the years advertising on his program (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Radio Free Torricelli'' (editorial, Jan. 11) suggested that Senator Robert G. Torricelli selected the ''peculiar forum'' of the ''Imus in the Morning'' radio show to answer questions about a controversial meeting with a contributor.</p>
        <p>Peculiar? Really? So ''peculiar'' that The New York Times Company has spent hundreds of thousands of dollars over the years advertising on it? So out of the mainstream that Time magazine has designated its host as one of the 25 most influential people in America?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Radio Free Torricelli'' (editorial, Jan. 11) suggested that Senator Robert G. Torricelli selected the ''peculiar forum'' of the ''Imus in the Morning'' radio show to answer questions about a controversial meeting with a contributor.</p>
        <p>Peculiar? Really? So ''peculiar'' that The New York Times Company has spent hundreds of thousands of dollars over the years advertising on it? So out of the mainstream that Time magazine has designated its host as one of the 25 most influential people in America?</p>
        <p>I agree that it makes your point to characterize the senator's appearance as having occurred on a wacky radio show with an audience of people who saw Woody Allen on the grassy knoll. It is not, however, even close to the truth.</p>
        <p>DON IMUS  New York, Jan. 11, 2002</p>
      </block>
